WEBVTT

1
00:00:19.436 --> 00:00:23.941
We've become bored with watching
actors give us phony emotions.

2
00:00:24.691 --> 00:00:28.403
We're tired of pyrotechnics
and special effects.

3
00:00:28.946 --> 00:00:33.784
While the world he inhabits is,
in some respects, counterfeit,

4
00:00:34.743 --> 00:00:37.663
there's nothing fake about
Truman himself.

5
00:00:38.372 --> 00:00:40.958
No scripts, no cue cards.

6
00:00:41.750 --> 00:00:44.795
It isn't always Shakespeare,
but it's genuine.

7
00:00:45.546 --> 00:00:46.964
It's a life.

8
00:00:50.842 --> 00:00:52.761
<i>I’m not going to make it.</i>

9
00:00:54.263 --> 00:00:55.973
<i>You’re going to have to go on
without me.</i>

10
00:01:01.311 --> 00:01:02.813
<i>No way, mister.</i>

11
00:01:03.647 --> 00:01:07.484
<i>You’re going to the top of this mountain,
broken legs and all.</i>

12
00:01:11.989 --> 00:01:15.158
We find many viewers leave him on
all night for comfort.

13
00:01:16.994 --> 00:01:19.162
<i>You’re crazy, you know that?</i>

14
00:01:22.416 --> 00:01:26.587
For me, there is no difference
between a private life and a public life.

15
00:01:26.670 --> 00:01:30.007
My life, is my life, is <i>The Truman Show.</i>

16
00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:32.426
<i>The Truman Show</i> is a lifestyle.

17
00:01:32.509 --> 00:01:34.845
It's a noble life. It is

18
00:01:37.723 --> 00:01:39.308
a truly blessed life.

19
00:01:39.391 --> 00:01:42.019
<i>Yeah, tell me something I don’t know.</i>

20
00:01:43.395 --> 00:01:46.148
<i>All right. Promise me one thing, though.</i>

21
00:01:46.857 --> 00:01:49.443
<i>If I die before I reach the summit,</i>

22
00:01:50.402 --> 00:01:53.488
<i>you’ll use me
as an alternative source of food.</i>

23
00:01:54.573 --> 00:01:55.657
<i>Gross.</i>

24
00:01:59.161 --> 00:02:01.371
It's all true. It's all real.

25
00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:05.292
Nothing here is fake.
Nothing you see on this show is fake.

26
00:02:05.667 --> 00:02:07.044
It's merely controlled.

27
00:02:15.302 --> 00:02:18.263
Eat me, damn it. That's an order.

28
00:02:21.224 --> 00:02:23.393
Maybe just your love handles.

29
00:02:24.311 --> 00:02:27.939
I have love handles? Yeah. Little ones.

30
00:02:28.231 --> 00:02:30.692
MERYL: Truman. You're going to be late.

31
00:02:31.276 --> 00:02:32.944
Okay!

32
00:02:35.072 --> 00:02:36.365
(SIGHS)

33
00:02:47.167 --> 00:02:48.960
-Good morning.
-Morning.

34
00:02:49.044 --> 00:02:50.212
Good morning.

35
00:02:50.295 --> 00:02:54.591
In case I don't see you, good afternoon,
good evening, and good night.

36
00:02:54.716 --> 00:02:55.676
(ALL LAUGHING)

37
00:02:55.759 --> 00:02:56.843
Yeah.

38
00:02:56.927 --> 00:02:58.512
-Morning, Truman.
-Morning, Spencer.

39
00:02:58.595 --> 00:02:59.638
(PLUTO BARKING)

40
00:02:59.721 --> 00:03:00.722
Hey, Pluto. No, get down.

41
00:03:00.806 --> 00:03:02.557
-He won't hurt you.
-Get down.

42
00:03:02.641 --> 00:03:04.184
I know.

43
00:03:04.309 --> 00:03:06.561
-It's just me.
-Come on, Pluto.

44
00:03:17.948 --> 00:03:19.157
(LOUD CRASHING)

45
00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:30.127
What is it?

46
00:03:51.273 --> 00:03:52.858
<i>MAN ON RADIO:
Here’s a news flash just in.</i>

47
00:03:52.941 --> 00:03:55.527
<i>An aircraft in trouble
began shedding parts</i>

48
00:03:55.610 --> 00:03:58.697
<i>as it ﬂew over Seahaven
just a few moments ago.</i>

49
00:03:58.780 --> 00:04:00.490
<i>Luckily, no one was hurt.</i>

50
00:04:00.574 --> 00:04:02.659
<i>But, hey, how do you feel today?</i>

51
00:04:02.993 --> 00:04:05.078
<i>That’s good.
You thinking of flying somewhere?</i>

52
00:04:05.162 --> 00:04:06.705
-Nope.
<i>-No? Good.</i>

53
00:04:06.788 --> 00:04:08.874
<i>This is Classical Clive
with Classical Drive</i>

54
00:04:08.957 --> 00:04:11.293
<i>so why don’t you forget
about the perils of flying,</i>

55
00:04:11.376 --> 00:04:14.379
<i>settle back,
and let this music calm you down?</i>

56
00:04:15.255 --> 00:04:17.257
<i>(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

57
00:04:18.759 --> 00:04:21.178
<i>-Dog Fancy,</i> please.
<i>-Dog Fancy.</i>

58
00:04:21.261 --> 00:04:24.097
-Thank you very much.
-Thank you very much.

59
00:04:24.848 --> 00:04:27.017
Give me a paper there, will you, Earl?

60
00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:30.061
And one of these for the wife.

61
00:04:30.145 --> 00:04:31.938
Loves her fashion mags.

62
00:04:32.022 --> 00:04:33.565
Will that be all for you, Truman?

63
00:04:33.648 --> 00:04:36.026
-That's the whole kit and caboodle.
-Catch you later.

64
00:04:36.109 --> 00:04:38.153
Okay. Yeah.

65
00:04:45.202 --> 00:04:46.661
MAN: Good morning.

66
00:04:47.871 --> 00:04:49.831
-Hank.
-HANK: Morning, Truman.

67
00:04:50.499 --> 00:04:53.376
-Good morning, Truman.
-How are you guys?

68
00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:55.712
-Beautiful day, isn't it?
-Always.

69
00:04:55.796 --> 00:04:57.255
And how's your lovely wife?

70
00:04:58.632 --> 00:05:00.425
Good. How about yours?

71
00:05:00.509 --> 00:05:03.011
-Couldn't be better.
-Fine.

72
00:05:03.094 --> 00:05:04.930
-Nice talking to you, Truman.
-You, too.

73
00:05:05.013 --> 00:05:06.139
We must go now.

74
00:05:06.223 --> 00:05:09.851
Think about that policy. Okay,
that's two for one. That's a good deal.

75
00:05:09.935 --> 00:05:12.145
-Doppelgänger special.
-Right.

76
00:05:12.229 --> 00:05:13.396
Hi.

77
00:05:16.024 --> 00:05:18.610
Hey, fellows. You going in? Go ahead.

78
00:05:19.569 --> 00:05:21.988
-Go ahead.
-No, you first, please.

79
00:05:22.113 --> 00:05:23.740
I'm not that anxious to get there.

80
00:05:39.214 --> 00:05:40.382
(SOFTLY) Yes, hello.

81
00:05:40.465 --> 00:05:44.010
Could I have directory assistance
for Fiji, please? Fiji islands.

82
00:05:44.094 --> 00:05:45.512
Truman, did you see this?

83
00:05:48.181 --> 00:05:49.474
I'm sorry, ma'am.

84
00:05:49.558 --> 00:05:52.561
If he's in a coma,
he's probably uninsurable.

85
00:05:54.104 --> 00:05:56.690
Hello? Yes. Fiji, please.

86
00:05:57.065 --> 00:05:59.860
Do you have a listing for
Lauren Garland?

87
00:06:01.069 --> 00:06:02.612
Nothing listed?

88
00:06:03.697 --> 00:06:06.783
Okay. Do you have a Sylvia Garland?

89
00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:08.451
"S" for Sylvia.

90
00:06:09.953 --> 00:06:11.162
Nothing?

91
00:06:13.123 --> 00:06:14.749
Okay. Thank you.

92
00:06:38.148 --> 00:06:39.316
(COUGHS)

93
00:06:41.026 --> 00:06:42.235
(COUGHS)

94
00:06:50.619 --> 00:06:52.537
-Lawrence.
-Hey, Burbank.

95
00:06:52.621 --> 00:06:56.041
Got a prospect in Wells Park
I need you to close.

96
00:06:58.460 --> 00:06:59.836
Wells Park?

97
00:07:02.839 --> 00:07:05.967
-On Harbor Island?
-You know another one?

98
00:07:06.051 --> 00:07:09.888
I can't do it.
I have an appointment. Dentist.

99
00:07:12.265 --> 00:07:16.061
You're going to lose a lot more than
your teeth if you don't meet your quota.

100
00:07:16.144 --> 00:07:17.729
Look, Truman,

101
00:07:17.938 --> 00:07:20.440
they're making cutbacks
at the end of this month.

102
00:07:20.523 --> 00:07:23.026
-Cutbacks?
-Yeah. Now, you need this.

103
00:07:23.735 --> 00:07:28.156
Besides, a half-hour across the bay,
a little sea air would do you good.

104
00:07:29.532 --> 00:07:30.742
Thanks.

105
00:07:40.251 --> 00:07:41.419
Hello.

106
00:07:41.503 --> 00:07:44.673
Ferry's still here.
Thought I might have missed it.

107
00:07:45.006 --> 00:07:46.675
One-way or return?

108
00:07:47.759 --> 00:07:48.969
Return.

109
00:07:51.471 --> 00:07:53.139
There you go, sir.

110
00:08:34.764 --> 00:08:36.099
(SHUDDERS)

111
00:08:46.693 --> 00:08:48.028
(GROANING)

112
00:08:50.905 --> 00:08:54.451
-Do you need any help, sir?
-You go ahead. I'll be fine.

113
00:08:56.077 --> 00:08:57.287
(TITTERS) Yeah.

114
00:09:05.086 --> 00:09:06.212
(SIGHING)

115
00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:12.135
Hi, honey.

116
00:09:13.803 --> 00:09:16.306
Look what I got free at the checkout.

117
00:09:17.474 --> 00:09:21.061
It's a Chefs Pal.
It's a dicer, grater, peeler, all in one.

118
00:09:21.144 --> 00:09:23.897
Never needs sharpening,
dishwasher-safe.

119
00:09:23.980 --> 00:09:24.981
Wow!

120
00:09:26.107 --> 00:09:27.650
That's amazing.

121
00:09:28.818 --> 00:09:30.070
MERYL: Truman,

122
00:09:31.613 --> 00:09:33.281
you missed a spot.

123
00:09:35.408 --> 00:09:36.785
(MUTTERING)

124
00:09:47.504 --> 00:09:49.047
That is a beer.

125
00:09:51.174 --> 00:09:53.718
You know, I'm thinking
about getting out, Marlon.

126
00:09:53.802 --> 00:09:55.720
Yeah? Out of what?

127
00:09:56.012 --> 00:09:58.348
Out of my job, out of Seahaven.

128
00:09:58.932 --> 00:10:01.267
-Off this island. Out.
-Out of your job?

129
00:10:01.351 --> 00:10:04.437
What the hell's wrong with your job?
You have a great job, Truman.

130
00:10:04.521 --> 00:10:07.941
You have a desk job.
I'd kill for a desk job.

131
00:10:11.402 --> 00:10:12.487
Here you go.

132
00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:14.489
You should try stocking
vending machines for a living.

133
00:10:14.572 --> 00:10:16.407
-No, thanks.
-Now there's excitement.

134
00:10:16.491 --> 00:10:17.784
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

135
00:10:17.867 --> 00:10:20.495
Don't you ever get antsy? Itchy feet?

136
00:10:22.038 --> 00:10:23.832
Where's there to go?

137
00:10:25.708 --> 00:10:26.793
Fiji.

138
00:10:28.294 --> 00:10:30.839
Where the hell's Fiji? Near Florida?

139
00:10:36.427 --> 00:10:37.804
-See here?
-Yeah.

140
00:10:37.887 --> 00:10:39.347
This is us,

141
00:10:41.349 --> 00:10:43.560
and all the way around here,

142
00:10:44.144 --> 00:10:45.228
Fiji.

143
00:10:46.146 --> 00:10:49.899
You can't get any further away
before you start coming back.

144
00:10:50.108 --> 00:10:52.861
You know, there are still islands in Fiji

145
00:10:52.944 --> 00:10:54.988
where no human being
has ever set foot.

146
00:10:58.158 --> 00:11:00.368
So when are you going to go?

147
00:11:02.954 --> 00:11:04.747
It's not that simple.

148
00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:07.917
It takes money,

149
00:11:08.918 --> 00:11:10.211
planning.

150
00:11:10.712 --> 00:11:12.589
I can't just up and go.

151
00:11:13.423 --> 00:11:14.591
Right.

152
00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:18.219
I'm going to do it.
Don't worry about that.

153
00:11:18.928 --> 00:11:21.514
Bonus time is just around the corner.

154
00:11:26.227 --> 00:11:29.522
-MARLON: You coming for a drink?
-TRUMAN: No, I can't tonight.

155
00:11:48.958 --> 00:11:51.127
<i>KIRK: I don’t like
the look of that weather, son.</i>

156
00:11:51.211 --> 00:11:52.420
I think we should head back.

157
00:11:52.503 --> 00:11:55.048
-No, Dad. Not yet.
-No, come on. We should go back.

158
00:11:55.131 --> 00:11:57.675
-A bit farther, please?
-Son, listen.

159
00:11:58.134 --> 00:11:59.969
-Okay.
-Yes.

160
00:12:00.553 --> 00:12:01.930
(THUNDER ROARING)

161
00:12:02.555 --> 00:12:04.140
Daddy!

162
00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:43.596
(EXCLAIMING)

163
00:13:01.364 --> 00:13:02.699
(LAUGHING)

164
00:13:04.367 --> 00:13:05.702
(THUNDER ROARING)

165
00:13:18.798 --> 00:13:21.384
You’re soaked. Where have you been?

166
00:13:21.467 --> 00:13:23.678
I figure we can
scrape together $8,000...

167
00:13:23.761 --> 00:13:25.138
Every time you and Marlon
get together...

168
00:13:25.221 --> 00:13:27.307
We can burn around the world
for a year on that.

169
00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:31.144
And then what, Truman?
We'd be where we were five years ago.

170
00:13:31.561 --> 00:13:35.690
-You're talking like a teenager.
-Maybe I feel like a teenager.

171
00:13:36.274 --> 00:13:38.735
We have mortgage payments, Truman.

172
00:13:39.027 --> 00:13:40.403
We have car payments.

173
00:13:40.486 --> 00:13:43.614
What, we're just going to walk away
from our financial obligations?

174
00:13:43.698 --> 00:13:45.700
It would be an adventure.

175
00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:50.830
I thought we were going to try for a
baby. Isn't that enough of an adventure?

176
00:13:51.748 --> 00:13:54.250
That can wait. I want to get away.

177
00:13:54.334 --> 00:13:57.086
See some of the world, explore.

178
00:13:57.170 --> 00:14:00.089
Honey, you want to be an explorer?

179
00:14:01.466 --> 00:14:02.925
This'll pass.

180
00:14:04.010 --> 00:14:06.554
We all think like this now and then.

181
00:14:08.973 --> 00:14:11.768
Let's get you out of these wet clothes,

182
00:14:12.268 --> 00:14:13.686
come to bed.

183
00:14:15.021 --> 00:14:17.982
You never see anything anyway.
They always

184
00:14:18.066 --> 00:14:20.985
turn the camera and play music and,

185
00:14:21.444 --> 00:14:24.197
you know, the wind blows in,
and the curtains move

186
00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:25.698
and you don't see anything.

187
00:14:26.616 --> 00:14:28.618
<i>(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

188
00:14:30.703 --> 00:14:32.955
<i>-Dog Fancy,</i> please.
<i>-Dog Fancy.</i>

189
00:14:34.207 --> 00:14:35.541
Thank you.

190
00:14:36.292 --> 00:14:37.668
(DOG BARKING)

191
00:14:37.752 --> 00:14:39.879
-Paper, Earl, please.
-Paper.

192
00:14:41.172 --> 00:14:44.550
I might as well pick one of these up
while I'm at it.

193
00:14:44.675 --> 00:14:47.303
-For the wife?
-She's got to have them.

194
00:14:47.929 --> 00:14:50.973
-Anything else, Truman?
-That's the whole ball of wax.

195
00:14:51.474 --> 00:14:53.393
-Catch you later.
-Okay.

196
00:15:14.247 --> 00:15:15.331
Dad?

197
00:15:18.668 --> 00:15:20.378
What are you doing?

198
00:15:20.670 --> 00:15:23.714
What the... Get out of the way!

199
00:15:24.006 --> 00:15:25.341
Stop them!

200
00:15:27.844 --> 00:15:29.512
Stop those people!

201
00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:35.977
Open the doors!
Somebody, stop the bus!

202
00:15:36.394 --> 00:15:39.188
Stop the bus! Somebody, stop it!

203
00:15:40.106 --> 00:15:42.275
Somebody, stop the bus!

204
00:15:42.358 --> 00:15:43.693
(CAR HORN BLARING)

205
00:15:55.746 --> 00:15:58.666
And wasn't it funny...

206
00:16:04.630 --> 00:16:07.341
It doesn't sound insane at all, Truman.

207
00:16:07.550 --> 00:16:11.304
I see him 10 times a week
in 100 different faces.

208
00:16:11.471 --> 00:16:15.308
I almost hugged a perfect stranger
in the salon last Thursday.

209
00:16:15.391 --> 00:16:18.978
It was Dad. I swear.
Dressed like a homeless man.

210
00:16:19.479 --> 00:16:20.980
And you know what else was strange?

211
00:16:21.063 --> 00:16:23.065
A businessman and a woman
with a little dog

212
00:16:23.149 --> 00:16:25.776
came out of nowhere
and forced him onto a bus.

213
00:16:25.860 --> 00:16:28.654
It's about time they cleaned up
the trash downtown

214
00:16:28.738 --> 00:16:31.449
before we become
just like the rest of the country.

215
00:16:31.532 --> 00:16:34.076
They never found Dad's body.
Maybe somehow...

216
00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:35.161
God!

217
00:16:35.244 --> 00:16:38.539
I'm telling you, if it wasn't him,
it was his twin.

218
00:16:39.999 --> 00:16:44.045
-Did Dad have a brother?
-Truman, you know perfectly well

219
00:16:44.420 --> 00:16:48.799
that your father was an only child,
just like you.

220
00:16:51.511 --> 00:16:53.054
Now, sweetie,

221
00:16:53.721 --> 00:16:56.891
you're just feeling bad
because of what happened.

222
00:16:58.142 --> 00:17:01.103
You, sailing off into that storm.

223
00:17:04.273 --> 00:17:06.776
But I've never blamed you, Truman,

224
00:17:07.902 --> 00:17:09.946
and I don't blame you now.

225
00:17:51.654 --> 00:17:53.155
(DOOR OPENING)

226
00:17:56.200 --> 00:17:57.410
MERYL: Truman?

227
00:18:01.455 --> 00:18:03.666
What are you doing down here?

228
00:18:05.167 --> 00:18:06.794
Fixing the mower.

229
00:18:10.464 --> 00:18:12.675
-Saw my father today.
-I know.

230
00:18:16.012 --> 00:18:17.763
Your mother called.

231
00:18:19.599 --> 00:18:22.393
You really shouldn't upset her like that.

232
00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:25.062
Did you want... What did you want?

233
00:18:25.438 --> 00:18:27.023
I made macaroni.

234
00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:29.191
I'm not hungry.

235
00:18:30.026 --> 00:18:33.654
You know, you really ought to throw out
that mower.

236
00:18:34.822 --> 00:18:37.241
Get one of those new Elk Rotaries.

237
00:19:13.819 --> 00:19:15.404
What's he doing?

238
00:19:15.529 --> 00:19:18.491
See, they got rid of her,
but they couldn't erase the memory.

239
00:19:18.574 --> 00:19:20.242
The memory of who?

240
00:19:22.244 --> 00:19:23.579
(MAN SHUSHING)

241
00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:25.414
(TRUMPET PLAYING)

242
00:19:58.280 --> 00:19:59.407
(MUTED)

243
00:20:00.116 --> 00:20:02.118
(MARLON CONTINUES PLAYING)

244
00:20:10.668 --> 00:20:12.211
(GIRL GROANING)

245
00:20:12.962 --> 00:20:15.297
-TRUMAN: You okay? You all right?
-MERYL: Excuse me. Hi.

246
00:20:15.381 --> 00:20:17.633
-Hi.
-I'm so sorry I fell on you like that.

247
00:20:17.717 --> 00:20:20.845
-It's okay.
-I've just been such a klutz all day.

248
00:20:20.928 --> 00:20:22.430
It's all right.

249
00:20:22.513 --> 00:20:25.558
