<i>But right now,
it’s time for</i> Golden Oldies.

493
00:38:17.629 --> 00:38:20.298
<i>Tonight, we present
the enduring, much-loved classic,</i>

494
00:38:20.381 --> 00:38:22.467
Show Me the Way to Go Home.

495
00:38:22.550 --> 00:38:24.761
<i>A hymn of praise to small-town life,</i>

496
00:38:24.844 --> 00:38:27.138
<i>where we learn
that you don’t have to leave home</i>

497
00:38:27.222 --> 00:38:31.851
<i>to discover what the world’s all about,
and that no one is poor who has friends.</i>

498
00:38:32.477 --> 00:38:36.856
<i>Full of laughter and love, pain and
sadness, but ultimately redemption,</i>

499
00:38:36.940 --> 00:38:39.651
<i>we share the trials and tribulations
of the Abbott family.</i>

500
00:38:39.734 --> 00:38:42.654
<i>Note the touching performance
of Ronald Brierly as Uncle Bunny.</i>

501
00:38:42.737 --> 00:38:45.323
<i>That scene with the bowl of cherries
is going to have you</i>

502
00:38:45.406 --> 00:38:48.326
<i>splitting your sides
with laughter all over again.</i>

503
00:38:48.409 --> 00:38:52.372
<i>And there’ll be tears, too,
when David and Jennifer are reunited.</i>

504
00:38:52.455 --> 00:38:56.292
<i>But enough from me.
Let’s join the Abbotts in Camden village.</i>

505
00:39:15.436 --> 00:39:16.604
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

506
00:39:18.940 --> 00:39:20.233
(TUNING RADIO)

507
00:39:23.653 --> 00:39:25.405
Thank you, sweetie.

508
00:39:29.284 --> 00:39:32.620
I need to talk to you,
but let's go outside.

509
00:39:33.413 --> 00:39:37.458
-Sweetie, I'd love to, but I'm really late.
-What's your rush?

510
00:39:38.668 --> 00:39:39.878
Surgery.

511
00:39:39.961 --> 00:39:43.423
There was that elevator disaster
downtown. It was on the news last night.

512
00:39:43.506 --> 00:39:45.216
This cable just snapped.

513
00:39:45.300 --> 00:39:47.844
This elevator,
it just plummeted down 10 flights.

514
00:39:47.927 --> 00:39:50.388
The non-union workers. Just monsters.

515
00:39:50.471 --> 00:39:53.099
That building, it's right next door
to where you work.

516
00:39:53.182 --> 00:39:55.184
Can you imagine
if you had been in there?

517
00:39:55.268 --> 00:39:56.811
It's not even worth thinking about.

518
00:39:56.895 --> 00:39:59.814
Anyway, I have an amputation
on one of the young women

519
00:39:59.898 --> 00:40:03.401
who was in that elevator.
She's very young. It's very sad.

520
00:40:03.484 --> 00:40:06.946
-Anyway, wish me luck.
-I'II cross my fingers for you.

521
00:40:45.652 --> 00:40:46.778
(BRAKES SQUEALING)

522
00:40:47.695 --> 00:40:49.155
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

523
00:40:49.238 --> 00:40:52.408
Excuse me. Hi. Excuse me.
May I help you?

524
00:40:54.077 --> 00:40:58.206
Yes. I'm looking for my wife,
Nurse Burbank. It's very important.

525
00:40:58.289 --> 00:41:01.668
I'm afraid that that's not possible.
She's in pre-op.

526
00:41:02.460 --> 00:41:05.046
Sure. Okay, fine.

527
00:41:05.463 --> 00:41:08.132
-Can you pass along a message?
-I'II try.

528
00:41:08.216 --> 00:41:11.970
Can you tell her I had to go to Fiji,
and that I'll call her when I get there?

529
00:41:12.053 --> 00:41:15.723
-When you get to Fiji?
-You got it.

530
00:41:15.807 --> 00:41:19.268
-Fine. I'll tell her.
-Thank you so much.

531
00:41:46.045 --> 00:41:47.922
-Sorry.
-It's okay.

532
00:41:49.173 --> 00:41:51.509
Here, let me help you with that.

533
00:41:55.847 --> 00:41:57.181
MAN: He's here.

534
00:41:59.392 --> 00:42:00.351
WOMAN: I know.

535
00:42:00.435 --> 00:42:01.519
(WOMAN SHUSHING)

536
00:42:01.602 --> 00:42:02.854
Scalpel.

537
00:42:09.527 --> 00:42:13.197
I'm now making my primary incision

538
00:42:13.823 --> 00:42:16.868
just above the right knee.

539
00:42:17.744 --> 00:42:19.412
(UTENSIL CLANGING)

540
00:42:19.871 --> 00:42:20.872
WOMAN: Hold her.

541
00:42:21.956 --> 00:42:23.332
Nicely done.

542
00:42:23.875 --> 00:42:26.711
This isn't going to be pretty.
Unless you're family...

543
00:42:26.794 --> 00:42:29.297
It's just beautiful. Beautiful job.

544
00:42:29.380 --> 00:42:30.882
(MAN SIGHING)

545
00:42:31.215 --> 00:42:33.384
I'll just let someone else tidy up here.

546
00:42:34.302 --> 00:42:36.179
<i>(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

547
00:42:58.326 --> 00:43:00.828
-l'm sorry to keep you.
-That's okay.

548
00:43:02.872 --> 00:43:06.667
-How can I help?
-I would like to book a flight to Fiji.

549
00:43:08.836 --> 00:43:11.047
When would you like to leave?

550
00:43:12.006 --> 00:43:13.174
Today.

551
00:43:24.644 --> 00:43:25.728
(BEEPING)

552
00:43:30.942 --> 00:43:34.570
I'm sorry. I don't have anything
for at least a month.

553
00:43:35.029 --> 00:43:37.532
-A month?
-It's the busy season.

554
00:43:39.826 --> 00:43:41.953
You want to book the flight?

555
00:43:42.787 --> 00:43:46.499
It doesn't matter.
I'll make other arrangements, okay?

556
00:43:49.710 --> 00:43:52.630
MAN: Last call for Chicago!

557
00:43:52.964 --> 00:43:55.383
All aboard!

558
00:44:00.513 --> 00:44:01.848
Thank you.

559
00:44:04.725 --> 00:44:06.727
Windy city, here we come.

560
00:44:08.855 --> 00:44:10.064


561
00:44:13.609 --> 00:44:15.403
Hello. Hi.

562
00:44:17.405 --> 00:44:18.447
TRUMAN: Sisters.

563
00:44:18.531 --> 00:44:20.491
Mom, isn't that...

564
00:44:20.575 --> 00:44:22.493
WOMAN: (WHISPERING)
Face the front.

565
00:44:32.211 --> 00:44:33.921
(ENGINE STALLING)

566
00:44:49.687 --> 00:44:52.190
Everybody off. We've got a problem.

567
00:45:11.751 --> 00:45:13.294
I'm sorry, son.

568
00:45:27.141 --> 00:45:29.852
His father was from Chicago,
wasn't he?

569
00:45:30.102 --> 00:45:33.814
No. His dentist was from Pensacola.
His father was from Des Moines.

570
00:45:33.898 --> 00:45:35.983
But how come he wants to go
to Chicago?

571
00:45:36.067 --> 00:45:38.694
He's not going to Chicago.
He's not going anywhere.

572
00:45:38.778 --> 00:45:40.655
He has to have it out with Meryl.

573
00:45:41.656 --> 00:45:43.241
(PLUTO BARKING)

574
00:45:56.837 --> 00:45:58.005
Truman?

575
00:46:03.302 --> 00:46:06.514
-Honey, are you okay?
-Get in.

576
00:46:10.184 --> 00:46:11.394
Truman.

577
00:46:12.687 --> 00:46:13.813
Look.

578
00:46:17.400 --> 00:46:18.567
What?

579
00:46:19.735 --> 00:46:22.363
I predict that in just a moment,

580
00:46:24.031 --> 00:46:28.202
we will see a lady on a red bike,
followed by a man with flowers

581
00:46:29.161 --> 00:46:32.206
and a Volkswagen Beetle
with a dented fender.

582
00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:34.625
-Truman, please.
-Look.

583
00:46:40.423 --> 00:46:41.632
Lady,

584
00:46:43.134 --> 00:46:44.468
flowers,

585
00:46:46.178 --> 00:46:47.763
and...

586
00:46:50.224 --> 00:46:53.144
-Truman, this is silly.
-There it is!

587
00:46:53.227 --> 00:46:55.563
There's that dented Beetle! Yes!

588
00:46:55.771 --> 00:46:57.064
(WHOOPING)

589
00:46:58.232 --> 00:46:59.400
(LAUGHING)

590
00:47:02.945 --> 00:47:05.573
Don't you want to know how I did that?
I'll tell you.

591
00:47:05.656 --> 00:47:08.075
They're on a loop.
They go around the block.

592
00:47:08.159 --> 00:47:11.996
They come back. They go around again.
They just go round and round.

593
00:47:12.079 --> 00:47:13.456
Round and round.

594
00:47:13.539 --> 00:47:15.875
I invited Rita and Marion
for a barbecue on Sunday.

595
00:47:15.958 --> 00:47:18.419
-I'm gonna make my potato salad.
-I won't be here Sunday.

596
00:47:18.502 --> 00:47:20.463
I need you to remind me
we need more charcoal.

597
00:47:20.546 --> 00:47:23.424
Are you listening to a word I'm saying?

598
00:47:25.426 --> 00:47:28.929
You're upset because
you want to go to Fiji. Is that it?

599
00:47:31.390 --> 00:47:32.808
Okay, go.

600
00:47:35.061 --> 00:47:38.773
I think you should save for
a few months, and then go.

601
00:47:39.565 --> 00:47:41.609
There. Are you happy now?

602
00:47:41.942 --> 00:47:43.319
I'm going to go take a shower.

603
00:47:46.322 --> 00:47:47.865
Let's go now.

604
00:47:48.282 --> 00:47:50.993
I'm ready to go now. Why wait?
Early bird gathers no moss.

605
00:47:51.077 --> 00:47:53.704
Rolling stone catches the worm, right?

606
00:47:55.539 --> 00:47:57.875
MERYL: (TITTERING)
Truman, what are you doing?

607
00:48:02.004 --> 00:48:03.214
Truman!

608
00:48:03.798 --> 00:48:07.134
Where shall we go?

609
00:48:08.511 --> 00:48:10.721
-Truman, where are we going?
-I don't really know.

610
00:48:10.805 --> 00:48:13.057
I guess I'm being spontaneous.

611
00:48:13.641 --> 00:48:17.019
Somebody, help me!
I'm being spontaneous!

612
00:48:17.103 --> 00:48:18.104
MERYL: Truman.

613
00:48:18.187 --> 00:48:19.563
Forget Fiji.

614
00:48:19.647 --> 00:48:22.566
-Can't very well drive to Fiji, can we?
-No.

615
00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:28.864
-What about Atlantic City?
-No, you hate to gamble.

616
00:48:28.948 --> 00:48:31.951
-That's right, I do, don't I?
-So why would you want to go there?

617
00:48:32.034 --> 00:48:36.247
Because I never have.
That's why people go places, isn't it?

618
00:48:36.997 --> 00:48:40.835
-Truman, I think I'm going to throw up.
-Me, too.

619
00:48:49.260 --> 00:48:51.637
Blocked at every turn.

620
00:48:52.805 --> 00:48:54.640
Beautifully synchronized,
don't you agree?

621
00:48:54.723 --> 00:48:57.726
-You're blaming me for the traffic?
-Should I?

622
00:49:04.692 --> 00:49:08.112
Truman, let's go home.

623
00:49:09.029 --> 00:49:12.241
You're right.
We could be stuck here for hours.

624
00:49:12.324 --> 00:49:14.660
It could be like this
all the way to Atlantic City.

625
00:49:14.743 --> 00:49:16.245
Let's go back.

626
00:49:17.496 --> 00:49:20.291
I'm sorry. I don't know what got into me.

627
00:49:24.003 --> 00:49:26.005
Can you please slow down?

628
00:49:26.922 --> 00:49:28.299
Yes, I can.

629
00:49:30.134 --> 00:49:33.596
-Truman, that's our turnoff.
-I changed my mind again.

630
00:49:33.679 --> 00:49:36.182
What's New Orleans like
this time of year? Mardi Gras!

631
00:49:36.265 --> 00:49:37.349
(WHOOPING)

632
00:49:37.433 --> 00:49:38.517
(GUFFAWING)

633
00:49:38.601 --> 00:49:40.102
(HONKING HORN)

634
00:49:43.564 --> 00:49:47.359
Look, Meryl, same road, no cars.

635
00:49:47.485 --> 00:49:48.861
It's magic.

636
00:49:49.361 --> 00:49:52.490
Look, you let me out.
You're not right in the head.

637
00:49:52.573 --> 00:49:54.867
You want to destroy yourself,
you do it on your own.

638
00:49:54.950 --> 00:49:57.077
I think I'd like a little company.

639
00:50:03.584 --> 00:50:07.838
MERYL: Truman,
you knew this would happen.

640
00:50:09.089 --> 00:50:11.967
You know you can't drive over water.

641
00:50:12.259 --> 00:50:14.887
Let's go home where you'll feel safe.

642
00:50:17.515 --> 00:50:19.600
-Give me your hand.
-Sweetie.

643
00:50:20.476 --> 00:50:21.644
Drive.

644
00:50:22.228 --> 00:50:23.437
Truman!

645
00:50:23.938 --> 00:50:26.941
We shouldn't be doing this!
Truman, we're breaking the law!

646
00:50:27.191 --> 00:50:28.734
-Oh, my!
-You can do it.

647
00:50:28.817 --> 00:50:30.861
-Please, don't!
-You can make it.

648
00:50:31.237 --> 00:50:32.488
Truman.

649
00:50:33.405 --> 00:50:34.532
We're over.

650
00:50:34.615 --> 00:50:37.952
-We're over the bridge.
-We're over?

651
00:50:38.536 --> 00:50:40.579
-We're over the bridge.
-We're over.

652
00:50:46.460 --> 00:50:48.212
Truman, what about that sign?

653
00:50:48.295 --> 00:50:50.965
I'm sure they're exaggerating.
We'll be fine.

654
00:50:52.550 --> 00:50:54.969
Exaggerating? Do you believe that?

655
00:50:55.052 --> 00:50:57.012
-Truman, let's go back!
-Can't go back!

656
00:50:57.137 --> 00:50:59.723
MERYL: Oh, my! Truman, we're on fire!

657
00:50:59.807 --> 00:51:01.225
-TRUMAN: It's okay.
-We're on fire!

658
00:51:01.308 --> 00:51:03.227
It's okay. It's just smoke.

659
00:51:03.310 --> 00:51:04.853
-You okay?
-Yes.

660
00:51:05.062 --> 00:51:06.897
-Want to do it again?
-No!

661
00:51:06.981 --> 00:51:08.274
(LAUGHING)

662
00:51:08.482 --> 00:51:11.318
Truman, stop! Oh, God!

663
00:51:13.320 --> 00:51:17.324
So what are we going to do for money
when we get to New Orleans?

664
00:51:18.158 --> 00:51:20.369
I have my Seahaven bank card.

665
00:51:21.078 --> 00:51:24.790
So what? We're just gonna eat
into our savings, is that it?

666
00:51:25.332 --> 00:51:27.918
I'm going to have to call your mother
when we get there.

667
00:51:28.002 --> 00:51:32.506
She's going to be worried sick. I don't
know how she's going to take this.

668
00:51:35.259 --> 00:51:36.844
(SIRENS BLARING)

669
00:51:43.851 --> 00:51:45.269
What now?

670
00:51:47.271 --> 00:51:48.939
<i>MAN ON PA: This is a red alert.</i>

671
00:51:49.023 --> 00:51:50.190
(HORN HONKING)

672
00:51:51.859 --> 00:51:54.236
MERYL: Truman,
it looks like a leak at the plant.

673
00:51:54.320 --> 00:51:56.447
Back up. Leak at the plant.

674
00:51:56.530 --> 00:51:58.949
-We had to shut her down.
-Is there any way around?

675
00:51:59.033 --> 00:52:01.744
-Whole area's being evacuated.
-Is there anything I can do?

676
00:52:01.827 --> 00:52:03.787
-No, ma'am.
-Thank you for your help.

677
00:52:03.871 --> 00:52:05.539
You're welcome, Truman.

678
00:52:06.957 --> 00:52:08.334
Truman.

679
00:52:10.878 --> 00:52:12.713
Truman!

680
00:52:13.130 --> 00:52:14.798
Truman, come back!

681
00:52:17.301 --> 00:52:18.719
Stop him!

682
00:52:20.054 --> 00:52:21.388
Truman!

683
00:52:22.181 --> 00:52:23.557
MAN: Catch him on the left!

684
00:52:31.231 --> 00:52:32.983
(TRUMAN EXCLAIMING)

685
00:52:40.074 --> 00:52:41.450
Stay away!

686
00:52:41.575 --> 00:52:43.410
<i>(CHATTERING ON RADIO)</i>

687
00:52:43.577 --> 00:52:44.912
(GRUNTING)

688
00:52:47.790 --> 00:52:48.874
No.

689
00:52:50.084 --> 00:52:51.293
No!

690
00:52:51.794 --> 00:52:53.420
<i>MAN ON RADIO: …now in custody.</i>

691
00:52:56.799 --> 00:53:00.594
Thank you both so much for your help.
I really appreciate it.

692
00:53:00.928 --> 00:53:04.598
He's lucky to be alive, ma'am.
Next time, we'll have to file charges.

693
00:53:04.682 --> 00:53:06.141
I understand.

694
00:53:06.433 --> 00:53:08.602
-Thanks again.
-Good night.

695
00:53:26.453 --> 00:53:29.039
Let me get you some help, Truman.

696
00:53:29.790 --> 00:53:31.375
You're not well.

697
00:53:33.836 --> 00:53:36.547
Why do you want to have a baby
with me?

698
00:53:37.631 --> 00:53:39.383
You can't stand me.

699
00:53:39.800 --> 00:53:41.427
That's not true.

700
00:53:46.098 --> 00:53:48.809
Why don't you let me fix you
some of this new Mococoa drink?

701
00:53:48.892 --> 00:53:52.146
All natural cocoa beans
from the upper slopes of Mt. Nicaragua.

702
00:53:52.229 --> 00:53:53.981
No artificial sweeteners.

703
00:53:54.064 --> 00:53:56.608
What the hell are you talking about?

704
00:53:57.151 --> 00:53:58.986
Who are you talking to?

705
00:53:59.069 --> 00:54:02.197
I've tasted other cocoas.
This is the best.

706
00:54:02.281 --> 00:54:05.993
What the hell does this have to do
with anything?

707
00:54:06.785 --> 00:54:08.787
Tell me what's happening!

708
00:54:08.954 --> 00:54:12.416
You're having a nervous breakdown,
that's what's happening.

709
00:54:12.499 --> 00:54:14.710
You're part of this, aren't you?

710
00:54:16.920 --> 00:54:18.881
-Truman.
-Meryl!

711
00:54:19.506 --> 00:54:21.967
You are scaring me.

712
00:54:22.050 --> 00:54:24.678
No. You're scaring me, Meryl.

713
00:54:25.053 --> 00:54:28.891
What are you going to do? Dice me?
Slice me and peel me?

714
00:54:28.974 --> 00:54:30.809
There are so many choices!

715
00:54:30.893 --> 00:54:32.019
<i>(MERYL SCREAMING)</i>

716
00:54:32.186 --> 00:54:33.812
<i>Do something!</i>

717
00:54:35.105 --> 00:54:36.190
<i>What?</i>

718
00:54:37.024 --> 00:54:38.859
<i>What did you say?</i>

719
00:54:39.193 --> 00:54:42.321
-Who were you talking to?
-Nothing. I didn't say anything.

720
00:54:42.404 --> 00:54:44.072
I didn't say anything.

721
00:54:44.156 --> 00:54:47.451
-You said "do something."
-No, I didn't. I wasn't talking to anybody.

722
00:54:47.534 --> 00:54:48.535
Talk to me!

723
00:54:48.619 --> 00:54:49.620
(BANGING ON DOOR)

724
00:54:49.703 --> 00:54:50.913
I don't know anything. Please stop.

725
00:54:50.996 --> 00:54:52.581
Stay where you are.

726
00:54:53.749 --> 00:54:55.250
Truman?

727
00:54:56.668 --> 00:54:57.961
Truman.

728
00:54:58.587 --> 00:55:02.257
Oh, thank God!

729
00:55:02.925 --> 00:55:04.468
(MERYL SOBBING)

730
00:55:05.385 --> 00:55:10.182
How can anyone expect me to carry on
under these conditions?

731
00:55:10.474 --> 00:55:12.476
It's unprofessional.

732
00:55:13.393 --> 00:55:14.728
MARLON: (HUSHING) It's okay.

733
00:55:17.606 --> 00:55:21.860
Everything's going to be okay.
It's all gonna be fine.

734
00:55:25.405 --> 00:55:27.574
I don't know what to think, Marlon.

735
00:55:31.703 --> 00:55:33.914
Maybe I'm losing my mind, but...

736
00:55:38.252 --> 00:55:41.588
It feels like the whole world
revolves around me somehow.

737
00:55:44.007 --> 00:55:46.677
That's a lot of world for one man,
Truman.

738
00:55:48.846 --> 00:55:50.931
Sure that's not wishful thinking?

739
00:55:51.348 --> 00:55:54.393
You wishing you'd made something
more out of yourself?

740
00:55:55.269 --> 00:55:57.437
Come on, who hasn't sat in the john,

741
00:55:57.521 --> 00:56:00.232
had an imaginary interview
on <i>Seahaven Tonight?</i>

742
00:56:00.691 --> 00:56:03.527
-Who hasn't wanted to be somebody?
-This is different.

743
00:56:03.610 --> 00:56:05.612
Everybody seems to be in on it.

744
00:56:09.992 --> 00:56:13.453
I've been your best friend
since we were 7 years old, Truman.

745
00:56:13.787 --> 00:56:15.622
The only way you and I
ever made it through school

746
00:56:15.706 --> 00:56:18.333
was by cheating off each other's
test papers.

747
00:56:19.501 --> 00:56:21.378
Jesus, they were identical.

748
00:56:23.672 --> 00:56:25.883
But I always felt safe knowing that.

749
00:56:26.884 --> 00:56:29.928
'Cause whatever the answer was,
we were right together,

750
00:56:30.178 --> 00:56:31.972
and we were wrong together.

751
00:56:33.640 --> 00:56:36.685
Remember that time I stayed up
with you all night in your tent

752
00:56:36.768 --> 00:56:39.062
because you wanted to play North Pole?

753
00:56:39.730 --> 00:56:41.231
And I got pneumonia?

754
00:56:43.275 --> 00:56:44.651
You remember that?

755
00:56:45.527 --> 00:56:47.988
You were out of school for
about a month.

756
00:56:54.369 --> 00:56:57.164
You're the closest thing I ever had
to a brother, Truman.

757
00:57:03.670 --> 00:57:05.297
I know that things

758
00:57:06.465 --> 00:57:10.552
haven't really worked out for either of us
like we used to dream they would.

759
00:57:11.511 --> 00:57:15.349
I know that feeling, when it's like
everything's slipping away

760
00:57:16.600 --> 00:57:18.727
and you don't want to believe it,

761
00:57:19.353 --> 00:57:22.064
so you look for answers
somewhere else, but...

762
00:57:28.570 --> 00:57:30.072
CHRISTOF: The point is,

763
00:57:30.781 --> 00:57:33.408
I'd gladly walk in front of traffic for you.

764
00:57:39.456 --> 00:57:43.251
<i>The point is, I would gladly
step in front of traffic for you, Truman.</i>

765
00:57:44.419 --> 00:57:47.673
And the last thing I'd ever do
is lie to you.

766
00:57:50.133 --> 00:57:52.678
And the last thing that I would ever do

767
00:57:55.555 --> 00:57:56.807
is lie to you.

768
00:58:00.060 --> 00:58:02.062
I mean, think about it, Truman.

769
00:58:02.562 --> 00:58:04.356
If everybody is in on it,

770
00:58:07.109 --> 00:58:09.027
I'd have to be in on it, too.

771
00:58:15.158 --> 00:58:16.243
(SIGHING)

772
00:58:18.078 --> 00:58:20.247
I'm not in on it, Truman, because

773
00:58:21.665 --> 00:58:23.041
there is no "it."

774
00:58:27.170 --> 00:58:29.548
You were right about one thing, though.

775
00:58:30.257 --> 00:58:31.591
What's that?

776
00:58:33.301 --> 00:58:35.345
The thing that started all this.

777
00:58:50.777 --> 00:58:53.572
Yep. I found him for you, Truman.

778
00:58:53.947 --> 00:58:55.866
That's why I came by tonight.

779
00:58:56.742 --> 00:58:59.119
I'm sure he's got quite a story to tell.

780
00:59:02.956 --> 00:59:04.291
Go to him.

781
00:59:10.922 --> 00:59:12.466
Easy on the fog.

782
00:59:14.301 --> 00:59:16.178
Stand by, crane cam.

783
00:59:17.637 --> 00:59:19.014
Crane cam.

784
00:59:26.980 --> 00:59:28.356
Button cam 3.

785
00:59:40.869 --> 00:59:42.954
I never stopped believing.

786
00:59:46.083 --> 00:59:49.044
CHRISTOF: And wide, curb cam 8.

787
00:59:49.669 --> 00:59:50.879
My son.

788
00:59:51.505 --> 00:59:52.589
(SIGHING)

789
00:59:52.672 --> 00:59:54.674
-Move in for a close-up?
-No.

790
00:59:56.676 --> 00:59:58.095
Move back

791
00:59:59.262 --> 01:00:00.722
and fade up music.

792
01:00:00.847 --> 01:00:02.349
(MUSIC PLAYING)

793
01:00:06.520 --> 01:00:08.146
And now go in close.

794
01:00:09.397 --> 01:00:11.316
<i>KIRK: (SOBBING)
All those years wasted.</i>

795
01:00:13.568 --> 01:00:16.863
<i>I’ll make it up to you, son. I swear.</i>

796
01:00:23.120 --> 01:00:24.204
<i>Dad.</i>

797
01:00:25.664 --> 01:00:26.706
CHRISTOF: Yes!

798
01:00:36.508 --> 01:00:37.676
Bravo.

799
01:00:38.093 --> 01:00:40.262
That will win the ratings period.

800
01:00:40.971 --> 01:00:42.055
MAN: Congratulations.

801
01:00:42.139 --> 01:00:44.224
CH RISTOF: Okay, everybody,
quiet down. Let's concentrate.

802
01:00:44.307 --> 01:00:46.101
-MAN 1: Great television.
-CHLOE: That was good work.

803
01:00:46.852 --> 01:00:48.979
MAN 2: Let's get some
champagne up here.

804
01:00:49.062 --> 01:00:50.522
WOMAN: Congratulations.

805
01:00:51.815 --> 01:00:55.527
-MOSES: Well done, Christof.
-It was brilliant. It just broke my heart.

806
01:00:59.239 --> 01:01:00.866
-Well done, everyone!
-Bravo!

807
01:01:00.949 --> 01:01:02.242
MOSES: Congratulations.

808
01:01:20.343 --> 01:01:23.597
<i>MAN ON TV:
1.7 billion were there for his birth.</i>

809
01:01:27.475 --> 01:01:31.021
<i>220 countries tuned in for his first step.</i>

810
01:01:31.104 --> 01:01:34.482
<i>The world stood still for that stolen kiss.</i>

811
01:01:34.858 --> 01:01:37.694
<i>And as he grew, so did the technology.</i>

812
01:01:37.777 --> 01:01:39.362
<i>An entire human life</i>

813
01:01:39.446 --> 01:01:42.365
<i>recorded on an intricate network
of hidden cameras</i>

814
01:01:42.449 --> 01:01:46.286
<i>and broadcast live and unedited,
24 hours a day,</i>

815
01:01:46.369 --> 01:01:49.623
<i>seven days a week,
to an audience around the globe.</i>

816
01:01:50.290 --> 01:01:53.126
<i>Coming to you now
from Seahaven island,</i>

817
01:01:53.335 --> 01:01:56.588
<i>enclosed in the largest studio
ever constructed,</i>

818
01:01:56.671 --> 01:01:58.924
<i>and along with the Great Wall of China,</i>

819
01:01:59.007 --> 01:02:02.302
<i>one of only two manmade structures
visible from space,</i>

820
01:02:03.011 --> 01:02:06.223
<i>now in its 30th great year,</i>

821
01:02:06.306 --> 01:02:08.225
<i>it’s</i> The Truman Show.

822
01:02:12.979 --> 01:02:14.898
What a week it's been.
I don't know about you,

823
01:02:14.981 --> 01:02:16.858
l was on pins and needles
the entire time.

824
01:02:17.400 --> 01:02:20.153
<i>Hello and good evening.
I’m your host Mike Michaelson,</i>

825
01:02:20.237 --> 01:02:21.613
<i>and welcome to</i> Trutalk.

826
01:02:21.696 --> 01:02:24.199
<i>Our forum for issues growing
out of the show.</i>

827
01:02:24.282 --> 01:02:26.868
<i>But tonight,
something very special indeed.</i>

828
01:02:26.993 --> 01:02:31.248
A rare and exclusive interview
with the show's conceiver and creator.

829
01:02:31.957 --> 01:02:35.293
So come with us now as we go live
to the lunar room

830
01:02:35.377 --> 01:02:38.755
<i>on the 221st floor
of the omni-cam ecosphere.</i>

831
01:02:38.838 --> 01:02:42.467
<i>That’s where we’ll find the world’s
greatest tele-visionary.</i>

832
01:02:42.676 --> 01:02:45.595
<i>The designer and architect
of the world within a world</i>

833
01:02:45.679 --> 01:02:47.806
<i>that is Seahaven Island: Christof.</i>

834
01:02:49.266 --> 01:02:52.102
<i>Before we begin, I’d like to thank you
on behalf of our audience,</i>

835
01:02:52.185 --> 01:02:54.020
<i>for granting this exclusive interview.</i>

836
01:02:54.104 --> 01:02:56.356
<i>We know how demanding
your schedule is</i>

837
01:02:56.439 --> 01:02:59.317
<i>and we all know how jealously
you guard your privacy.</i>

838
01:02:59.401 --> 01:03:01.695
<i>This, sir, is indeed an honor.</i>

839
01:03:01.861 --> 01:03:03.238
<i>Don ’t mention it.</i>

840
01:03:03.321 --> 01:03:06.241
<i>The catalyst for the recent
dramatic events on the show</i>

841
01:03:06.324 --> 01:03:08.410
<i>has been Truman’s father, Kirk,</i>

842
01:03:08.493 --> 01:03:11.871
<i>and his attempts to infiltrate the show.
But before we get into that,</i>

843
01:03:11.955 --> 01:03:14.624
<i>I think it’s worth noting
this is not the first time</i>

844
01:03:14.708 --> 01:03:18.044
<i>someone from the outside
has attempted to reach Truman, is it?</i>

845
01:03:18.128 --> 01:03:20.005
<i>CHRISTOF: We have had
our close calls in the past.</i>

846
01:03:20.088 --> 01:03:23.174
Truman! It's television! Yes!

847
01:03:24.050 --> 01:03:27.095
Yes! I did it! I'm on <i>The Truman Show!</i>

848
01:03:27.887 --> 01:03:29.931
<i>MIKE: But there’s never been anything
to compare with</i>

849
01:03:30.015 --> 01:03:31.975
<i>this most recent breach in security.</i>

850
01:03:32.058 --> 01:03:35.228
<i>The first intruder
to be a former cast member.</i>

851
01:03:35.854 --> 01:03:36.980
A dead one at that.

852
01:03:37.063 --> 01:03:40.650
<i>Got to say, writing Kirk back in,
masterstroke.</i>

853
01:03:41.109 --> 01:03:43.611
<i>Since Kirk started this whole crisis
in Truman’s life,</i>

854
01:03:43.695 --> 01:03:46.990
<i>I came to the conclusion that he was
the only one who could end it.</i>

855
01:03:47.073 --> 01:03:48.199
Truman!

856
01:03:48.283 --> 01:03:49.576
Truman, no!

857
01:03:50.577 --> 01:03:51.745
That's off-limits.

858
01:03:51.828 --> 01:03:55.540
-Why? What's over there?
-Nothing. It's dangerous. That's all.

859
01:03:55.790 --> 01:03:58.001
You've got to know
your limitations, Truman.

860
01:03:58.084 --> 01:04:00.128
<i>MIKE: But let’s remind viewers
of exactly why</i>

861
01:04:00.211 --> 01:04:02.213
<i>Dad was written out in the first place.</i>

862
01:04:02.339 --> 01:04:05.675
<i>CHRISTOF: As Truman grew up,
we were forced to manufacture ways</i>

863
01:04:05.759 --> 01:04:07.510
<i>to keep him on the island.</i>

864
01:04:07.802 --> 01:04:10.513
I'd like to be an explorer,
like the great Magellan.

865
01:04:10.597 --> 01:04:12.098
You're too late.

866
01:04:12.182 --> 01:04:14.559
There's really nothing left to explore.

867
01:04:19.064 --> 01:04:21.691
<i>CHRISTOF: Finally, I came up with the
concept of Kirk’s drowning.</i>

868
01:04:21.775 --> 01:04:24.903
<i>MIKE: Most effective. Truman’s been
terrified of the water ever since.</i>

869
01:04:24.986 --> 01:04:27.822
<i>CHRISTOF: When Kirk read the
synopsis for the</i> Death At Sea <i>episode,</i>

870
01:04:27.906 --> 01:04:31.368
<i>he was disappointed, to say the least.</i>

871
01:04:32.619 --> 01:04:35.038
<i>I’m sure that’s what caused him
to break back onto the set.</i>

872
01:04:35.121 --> 01:04:38.458
<i>MIKE: But how do you intend to explain
his 22-year absence?</i>

873
01:04:40.377 --> 01:04:42.670
-Amnesia.
<i>-Brilliant.</i>

874
01:04:43.463 --> 01:04:45.298
<i>Let’s take some viewer phone calls.</i>

875
01:04:45.382 --> 01:04:48.301
<i>Charlotte, North Carolina,
you’re on with Christof.</i>

876
01:04:49.386 --> 01:04:50.845
<i>MALE CHARLOTTE CALLER:
Yeah, hi, Christof.</i>

877
01:04:51.137 --> 01:04:54.641
<i>l was just wondering how many
cameras you got there in that town.</i>

878
01:04:55.100 --> 01:04:57.227
<i>Somewhere in the vicinity of 5,000.</i>

879
01:04:57.644 --> 01:05:02.357
<i>-That’s a lot of cameras.
-Remember, we started with just one.</i>

880
01:05:04.109 --> 01:05:06.152
<i>He was curious from birth.</i>

881
01:05:07.153 --> 01:05:10.782
<i>Premature by two weeks. It was almost
as if he couldn’t wait to get started.</i>

882
01:05:10.865 --> 01:05:13.159
<i>MIKE: And his eagerness to leave
his mother’s womb</i>

883
01:05:13.243 --> 01:05:15.745
<i>was the very reason he was the one
who was selected.</i>

884
01:05:15.829 --> 01:05:18.540
<i>CHRISTOF: In competition
with five other unwanted pregnancies,</i>

885
01:05:18.623 --> 01:05:21.418
<i>the casting of a show,
determined by an air date,</i>

886
01:05:21.543 --> 01:05:23.837
<i>Truman was the one who
arrived on cue.</i>

887
01:05:28.633 --> 01:05:31.511
<i>MIKE: Incidentally, I believe
Truman is the first child</i>

888
01:05:31.594 --> 01:05:34.097
<i>to have been legally adopted
by a corporation.</i>

889
01:05:34.180 --> 01:05:35.306
<i>That’s correct.</i>

890
01:05:35.390 --> 01:05:37.767
<i>The show has generated
enormous revenues,</i>

891
01:05:37.851 --> 01:05:41.104
<i>now equivalent to the gross national
product of a small country.</i>

892
01:05:41.187 --> 01:05:42.355
<i>People forget it takes</i>

893
01:05:42.439 --> 01:05:45.150
<i>the population of an entire country
to keep the show running.</i>

894
01:05:45.233 --> 01:05:48.903
<i>Since the show is on 24 hours a day
without commercial interruption,</i>

895
01:05:48.987 --> 01:05:52.532
<i>all those staggering revenues
are generated by product placement.</i>

896
01:05:52.949 --> 01:05:55.285
<i>That’s true.
Everything on the show is for sale.</i>

897
01:05:55.368 --> 01:05:58.663
<i>From the actors’ wardrobe, food
products, to the very homes they live in.</i>

898
01:05:58.746 --> 01:06:01.082
<i>All of it available in the</i> Truman <i>catalog</i>

899
01:06:01.166 --> 01:06:02.542
<i>and operators are standing by.</i>

900
01:06:02.625 --> 01:06:04.377
<i>Christof, let me ask you.</i>

901
01:06:04.794 --> 01:06:08.047
<i>Why do you think
that Truman has never come close</i>

902
01:06:08.548 --> 01:06:11.676
<i>to discovering the true nature
of his world until now?</i>

903
01:06:12.135 --> 01:06:15.180
<i>We accept the reality of the world
with which we are presented.</i>

904
01:06:15.263 --> 01:06:16.890
<i>It’s as simple as that.</i>

905
01:06:17.515 --> 01:06:19.142
<i>The Hague for Christof.</i>

906
01:06:19.225 --> 01:06:21.436
<i>Hello? The Hague?</i>

907
01:06:22.937 --> 01:06:26.524
<i>All right, we’ve lost that call. Let’s go
to Hollywood. You’re on</i> Trutalk.

908
01:06:26.608 --> 01:06:29.235
Hi, I'd just like to say one thing.

909
01:06:29.319 --> 01:06:30.987
You're a liar and a manipulator.

910
01:06:31.070 --> 01:06:33.364
<i>And what you’ve done to Truman
is sick.</i>

911
01:06:34.908 --> 01:06:37.035
<i>We remember this voice, don’t we?</i>

912
01:06:38.286 --> 01:06:40.788
<i>-How could we forget?
-MIKE: Let’s go to another call.</i>

913
01:06:40.872 --> 01:06:44.167
<i>No. It’s fine, Mike.</i>

914
01:06:44.584 --> 01:06:47.504
<i>I love to reminisce
with former members of the cast.</i>

915
01:06:48.755 --> 01:06:50.006
<i>Sylvia,</i>

916
01:06:50.965 --> 01:06:53.801
<i>as you announced
so melodramatically to the world,</i>

917
01:06:55.094 --> 01:06:58.348
<i>you think because you batted your eyes
at Truman once,</i>

918
01:06:59.724 --> 01:07:01.184
<i>flirted with him,</i>

919
01:07:01.518 --> 01:07:03.811
<i>stole a few minutes of airtime with him</i>

920
01:07:03.895 --> 01:07:07.065
<i>to thrust yourself and your politics
into the limelight,</i>

921
01:07:07.148 --> 01:07:11.110
<i>that you know him?
That you know what’s right for him?</i>

922
01:07:11.277 --> 01:07:13.780
<i>You really think you’re in a position
to judge him?</i>

923
01:07:13.863 --> 01:07:16.032
What right do you have to take a baby

924
01:07:16.282 --> 01:07:18.952
and turn his life
into some kind of mockery?

925
01:07:19.786 --> 01:07:21.579
Don't you ever feel guilty?

926
01:07:23.248 --> 01:07:27.001
<i>l have given Truman a chance
to lead a normal life.</i>

927
01:07:28.336 --> 01:07:31.381
<i>The world, the place you live in,</i>

928
01:07:32.465 --> 01:07:33.883
<i>is the sick place.</i>

929
01:07:36.010 --> 01:07:38.054
<i>Seahaven is the way
the world should be.</i>

930
01:07:38.137 --> 01:07:41.849
He's not a performer. He's a prisoner.
Look at what you've done to him!

931
01:07:41.933 --> 01:07:43.643
<i>He could leave at any time.</i>

932
01:07:43.851 --> 01:07:46.396
<i>If his was more than
just a vague ambition,</i>

933
01:07:46.479 --> 01:07:50.066
<i>if he was absolutely determined
to discover the truth,</i>

934
01:07:51.276 --> 01:07:53.486
<i>there’s no way we could prevent him.</i>

935
01:07:53.778 --> 01:07:56.447
<i>I think what distresses you,</i>

936
01:07:57.407 --> 01:08:00.660
<i>really, caller, is that ultimately</i>

937
01:08:01.911 --> 01:08:05.540
<i>Truman prefers his cell, as you call it.</i>

938
01:08:05.957 --> 01:08:07.667
SYLVIA: That's where you're wrong.

939
01:08:08.167 --> 01:08:10.920
You're so wrong,
and he'll prove you wrong.

940
01:08:11.337 --> 01:08:15.550
<i>MIKE: Aside from the heated comments
of a very vocal minority,</i>

941
01:08:15.758 --> 01:08:18.469
<i>it’s been
an overwhelmingly positive experience.</i>

942
01:08:18.678 --> 01:08:21.014
<i>Yes. For Truman
and for the viewing public.</i>

943
01:08:21.097 --> 01:08:23.016
<i>MIKE: Christof, I can’t thank you enough</i>

944
01:08:23.099 --> 01:08:25.560
<i>for giving so generously
of your time tonight.</i>

945
01:08:25.643 --> 01:08:28.521
<i>I think it’s safe to say that
now that this crisis is behind us</i>

946
01:08:28.605 --> 01:08:30.315
<i>and that Truman’s back to his old self,</i>

947
01:08:30.398 --> 01:08:33.443
<i>we can look forward
to some exciting new developments.</i>

948
01:08:33.526 --> 01:08:37.113
<i>CHRISTOF: Mike, the big news is
that Meryl will be leaving Truman</i>

949
01:08:37.196 --> 01:08:38.781
<i>in an upcoming episode.</i>

950
01:08:38.865 --> 01:08:41.534
<i>And a new romantic interest
will be introduced.</i>

951
01:08:42.201 --> 01:08:46.539
<i>I’m determined that television’s first
on-air conception will still take place.</i>

952
01:08:46.956 --> 01:08:50.960
<i>MIKE: Another television milestone
straight ahead. You heard it here first.</i>

953
01:08:51.044 --> 01:08:53.796
<i>It has been a singular honor
and a pleasure, sir.</i>

954
01:08:53.880 --> 01:08:56.466
<i>-Christof, thank you.
-Thank you, Mike.</i>

955
01:09:58.194 --> 01:09:59.779
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

956
01:10:14.919 --> 01:10:16.546
-MAN: Simeon.
-What?

957
01:10:20.967 --> 01:10:22.510
Is he looking at us?

958
01:10:22.844 --> 01:10:24.804
Jesus, do you think he knows?

959
01:10:26.305 --> 01:10:27.306
<i>Hello?</i>

960
01:10:27.807 --> 01:10:29.350
Better call Christof.

961
01:10:29.475 --> 01:10:31.477
<i>Hello? Come in, Major Burbank.</i>

962
01:10:32.520 --> 01:10:33.646
<i>(WHISTLING)</i>

963
01:10:43.656 --> 01:10:44.657
Jesus.

964
01:10:45.158 --> 01:10:47.326
<i>(TRUMAN CONTINUES WHISTLING)</i>

965
01:10:48.995 --> 01:10:51.914
-MAN: He's back to his old self.
-SIMEON: Thank God.

966
01:10:53.708 --> 01:10:55.209
(MAN LAUGHING)

967
01:10:59.756 --> 01:11:02.216
SIMEON: That's an unusual cat,
my man.

968
01:11:07.096 --> 01:11:10.349
<i>I hereby proclaim this planet…</i>

969
01:11:15.104 --> 01:11:17.899
<i>Trumania of the Burbank galaxy.</i>

970
01:11:20.359 --> 01:11:22.695
-Is he gonna go?
-Okay, hallway camera ready.

971
01:11:24.572 --> 01:11:25.948
<i>That one’s for free.</i>

972
01:11:26.032 --> 01:11:27.992
SIMEON: Keep up with him,
'cause he'll move fast.

973
01:11:28.075 --> 01:11:30.203
MAN: Stand by, all house cameras.

974
01:11:31.245 --> 01:11:33.456
-Morning!
-Good morning.

975
01:11:33.623 --> 01:11:35.291
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

976
01:11:35.374 --> 01:11:37.043
In case I don't see you...

977
01:11:37.126 --> 01:11:39.670
Good afternoon, good evening,
and good night.

978
01:11:42.089 --> 01:11:44.467
-Good afternoon...
-Good morning.

979
01:11:44.550 --> 01:11:46.677
...evening and good night.

980
01:11:47.345 --> 01:11:49.472
-Morning, Truman.
-Morning, Spencer.

981
01:11:49.555 --> 01:11:51.849
-How's it going?
-Let me check.

982
01:11:52.642 --> 01:11:54.185
Vital signs are good.

983
01:11:54.685 --> 01:11:55.728
(PLUTO BARKING)

984
01:11:55.812 --> 01:11:57.563
(EXCLAIMING) Pluto!

985
01:11:58.356 --> 01:11:59.982
BOTH: Good morning, Truman.

986
01:12:00.066 --> 01:12:02.819
-Look who's here.
-Beautiful day, isn't it?

987
01:12:03.110 --> 01:12:04.237
Every single day.

988
01:12:04.320 --> 01:12:07.240
The policy, we've thought about it
and we're gonna take it.

989
01:12:07.323 --> 01:12:08.616
-You're kidding?
-BOTH: No!

990
01:12:08.699 --> 01:12:11.410
Why don't we go up to my office
right now and we'll sign the papers?

991
01:12:11.494 --> 01:12:14.163
Next week would be much better.

992
01:12:14.247 --> 01:12:17.458
-All right. See you guys.
-Okay, bye now. See you next week.

993
01:12:17.542 --> 01:12:20.211
-Give me something to look forward to.
-You got it.

994
01:12:20.294 --> 01:12:22.004
See, this isn't about insurance.

995
01:12:22.421 --> 01:12:26.551
This is about the great variable:
when will death occur?

996
01:12:26.926 --> 01:12:29.011
Could be a week, a month, a year.

997
01:12:30.054 --> 01:12:31.305
Could be today.

998
01:12:33.558 --> 01:12:35.852
"Sunbather, minding his own business,

999
01:12:36.686 --> 01:12:39.772
"stabbed in the heart by the tip
of a runaway beach umbrella."

1000
01:12:39.856 --> 01:12:41.482
No way to guard against
that kind of thing.

1001
01:12:41.566 --> 01:12:42.692
(LAUGHING)

1002
01:12:44.569 --> 01:12:46.028
Sorry, excuse me.

1003
01:12:46.237 --> 01:12:48.531
Truman, this is Vivien.
Vivien, this is Truman.

1004
01:12:48.614 --> 01:12:50.950
The two of you are gonna be neighbors.

1005
01:12:51.033 --> 01:12:52.368
(EXCLAIMS)

1006
01:12:55.037 --> 01:12:58.749
I guess what I'm saying is that life is

1007
01:12:59.542 --> 01:13:00.793
fragile.

1008
01:13:02.545 --> 01:13:04.171
-LAWRENCE: Vivien, your office.
-Sorry.

1009
01:13:04.255 --> 01:13:07.300
What's that? I'm sorry.

1010
01:13:08.342 --> 01:13:09.468
You do?

1011
01:13:10.344 --> 01:13:13.306
Great. Let me take your information.

1012
01:13:29.614 --> 01:13:31.240
Ready, 2. Go to 2.

1013
01:13:35.703 --> 01:13:37.163
And back to medium.

1014
01:13:39.206 --> 01:13:40.583
And wide.

1015
01:13:44.295 --> 01:13:45.379
Psst.

1016
01:13:48.591 --> 01:13:51.344
I was just trying to train the kid to...

1017
01:13:52.261 --> 01:13:53.596
Never mind.

1018
01:13:56.807 --> 01:13:58.851
CHRISTOF: What's he doing
in the basement?

1019
01:13:59.143 --> 01:14:01.646
He moved down there
after Meryl packed up and left.

1020
01:14:01.729 --> 01:14:03.147
Why wasn't I told?

1021
01:14:03.230 --> 01:14:05.858
Any unpredictable behavior
has to be reported.

1022
01:14:07.276 --> 01:14:09.153
He's just sleeping, I thought.

1023
01:14:09.236 --> 01:14:11.781
-This the best shot we've got?
-What's to see?

1024
01:14:11.864 --> 01:14:15.493
-What's on the clock cam?
-It's an obstruction.

1025
01:14:15.993 --> 01:14:19.747
-What happened down there?
-He was just tidying up his garbage.

1026
01:14:20.748 --> 01:14:24.710
l was gonna call you, but halfway
through, he gave up, and he fell asleep.

1027
01:14:25.086 --> 01:14:28.255
CHRISTOF: I wanna check on the setups
for the insurance convention tomorrow.

1028
01:14:28.339 --> 01:14:29.715
-CHRISTOF: Yes.
-Yeah.

1029
01:14:30.716 --> 01:14:32.051
Nice move.

1030
01:14:41.143 --> 01:14:42.395
There you go.

1031
01:14:53.364 --> 01:14:54.740
Isolate the audio.

1032
01:14:56.075 --> 01:14:58.077
Give me a close-up on his torso.

1033
01:14:58.411 --> 01:14:59.578
(SNORING)

1034
01:15:00.913 --> 01:15:02.415
He's still breathing.

1035
01:15:02.498 --> 01:15:03.582
(SIGHING)

1036
01:15:04.625 --> 01:15:06.293
Where's Chloe? Call him.

1037
01:15:06.502 --> 01:15:09.755
-What do you want me to say?
-Tell him it's a wrong number.

1038
01:15:11.090 --> 01:15:12.842
<i>(TELEPHONE RINGING)</i>

1039
01:15:13.217 --> 01:15:14.802
What took you so long?

1040
01:15:15.261 --> 01:15:17.805
Just had to wait for it. They were busy.

1041
01:15:18.723 --> 01:15:21.142
Here. What's going on?

1042
01:15:21.976 --> 01:15:23.728
I don't know. They're...

1043
01:15:23.894 --> 01:15:26.856
He came down into the room. He did
nothing but stand around for a while.

1044
01:15:26.939 --> 01:15:28.983
CHRISTOF: Shut up and watch it.

1045
01:15:29.066 --> 01:15:31.152
SIMEON: Then we went to night vision.

1046
01:15:31.944 --> 01:15:33.362
He's asleep.

1047
01:15:34.989 --> 01:15:36.240
-There!
-SIMEON: What?

1048
01:15:36.657 --> 01:15:38.409
-Zoom in.
-On which?

1049
01:15:38.743 --> 01:15:40.327
Under the chair there.

1050
01:15:42.788 --> 01:15:44.123
Enhance it.

1051
01:15:46.667 --> 01:15:49.170
-Is it...
-My God.

1052
01:15:49.462 --> 01:15:50.796
(STUTTERS)

1053
01:15:50.963 --> 01:15:54.091
He couldn't have gone up the stairs.
He must still be in the room.

1054
01:15:54.175 --> 01:15:55.801
-Get Marlon over there.
-Right away.

1055
01:15:55.926 --> 01:15:57.595
(TIRES SCREECHING)

1056
01:16:11.484 --> 01:16:12.651
MARLON: Truman!

1057
01:16:13.527 --> 01:16:14.820
Surprise party!

1058
01:16:16.864 --> 01:16:18.157
Come on, buddy.

1059
01:16:18.407 --> 01:16:21.535
I got a six-pack of cold brewskis
with our name on them.

1060
01:16:21.660 --> 01:16:23.662
Come on, pal. Come on, buddy.

1061
01:16:23.746 --> 01:16:24.789
(SQUEAKING)

1062
01:16:24.872 --> 01:16:25.915
(SNORING)

1063
01:16:27.958 --> 01:16:29.043
Shit.

1064
01:16:32.338 --> 01:16:34.840
Marlon, find him. He's still in the room.

1065
01:16:39.220 --> 01:16:41.138
<i>Come out, come out, wherever you are.</i>

1066
01:16:41.222 --> 01:16:43.015
That's good. Keep it light.

1067
01:16:43.933 --> 01:16:46.393
<i>I know you’re in here.
I’m gonna find you.</i>

1068
01:16:49.980 --> 01:16:51.565
Check under the table.

1069
01:16:52.983 --> 01:16:54.610
The closet, behind you.

1070
01:16:58.614 --> 01:16:59.615
Huh.

1071
01:17:01.408 --> 01:17:02.493
Gee.

1072
01:17:03.285 --> 01:17:05.496
I wonder where he could possibly be.

1073
01:17:13.420 --> 01:17:15.673
The lawn cam, get me the lawn cam.

1074
01:17:23.347 --> 01:17:26.016
Don't look in the camera.
Say something. Keep it going.

1075
01:17:26.100 --> 01:17:27.226
<i>He’s gone.</i>

1076
01:17:27.726 --> 01:17:29.562
-Cut transmission!
-Cut transmission?

1077
01:17:29.645 --> 01:17:30.896
Cut it!

1078
01:17:33.357 --> 01:17:34.358
(GLASS SHATTERING)

1079
01:17:34.441 --> 01:17:35.985
MAN: Jesus! God in heaven!

1080
01:17:36.735 --> 01:17:39.071
-Everything's black.
-Give me the phone.

1081
01:17:39.196 --> 01:17:41.198
<i>(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

1082
01:17:48.706 --> 01:17:50.166
(ALL SPEAKING TOGETHER)

1083
01:17:51.917 --> 01:17:54.128
I don't know where he is, but he's gone.

1084
01:17:59.758 --> 01:18:00.718
(CLEARING THROAT)

1085
01:18:00.801 --> 01:18:03.596
All right. We've got
every available extra looking for him.

1086
01:18:03.679 --> 01:18:07.975
The principals are helping out. The
crew, too. So every sector's covered.

1087
01:18:08.642 --> 01:18:11.353
-What about prop cars?
-Yes, they've been accounted for.

1088
01:18:11.437 --> 01:18:12.855
He has to be on foot.

1089
01:18:12.938 --> 01:18:15.858
He has the world's most
recognizable face. He can't disappear.

1090
01:18:20.613 --> 01:18:22.198
(SIRENS BLARING)

1091
01:18:45.221 --> 01:18:46.680
(DOG BARKING)

1092
01:18:51.727 --> 01:18:52.811
Go.

1093
01:18:53.687 --> 01:18:57.316
Hunt him. Yeah. Go find him, Pluto.

1094
01:18:57.900 --> 01:18:59.109
Good dog!

1095
01:18:59.193 --> 01:19:00.444
All this fuss.

1096
01:19:01.278 --> 01:19:03.280
If he could just hear my voice.

1097
01:19:04.240 --> 01:19:05.449
Truman!

1098
01:19:06.742 --> 01:19:07.993
Truman!

1099
01:19:08.577 --> 01:19:10.871
Let me try. Truman!

1100
01:19:12.164 --> 01:19:13.999
It's me, Dad!

1101
01:19:16.293 --> 01:19:17.503
Let's talk.

1102
01:19:19.171 --> 01:19:20.673
Yeah, I know.

1103
01:19:22.383 --> 01:19:24.301
Just about done with the square.

1104
01:19:24.385 --> 01:19:26.971
<i>Got to go back to Barrymore,
check the interiors.</i>

1105
01:19:27.054 --> 01:19:29.265
<i>-He’s got to be in there.</i>
-Barrymore.

1106
01:19:29.682 --> 01:19:31.809
But what about the college?
Who's watching that?

1107
01:19:31.892 --> 01:19:32.893
<i>I don’t know.</i>

1108
01:19:32.977 --> 01:19:35.312
-Send somebody over there, okay?
<i>-All right.</i>

1109
01:19:39.566 --> 01:19:41.944
Take another man
and get down there now, all right?

1110
01:19:42.027 --> 01:19:44.280
I don't give a damn.
Just find the son of a bitch.

1111
01:19:44.363 --> 01:19:45.322
MAN: Get some batteries.

1112
01:19:45.406 --> 01:19:48.117
This guy's not gonna glow in the dark.
Get them down here.

1113
01:19:48.200 --> 01:19:50.911
SIMEON: I don't know what's going on.
Reroute it back to me.

1114
01:19:50.995 --> 01:19:54.206
We need more light.
We'll never find him this way.

1115
01:19:59.503 --> 01:20:00.879
What time is it?

1116
01:20:01.213 --> 01:20:03.507
It's way too early for that.

1117
01:20:10.222 --> 01:20:11.390
Cue the sun.

1118
01:20:14.935 --> 01:20:16.562
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

1119
01:20:17.980 --> 01:20:19.356
What time is it?

1120
01:20:20.357 --> 01:20:22.067
MOSES: Christof, what's going on?

1121
01:20:22.609 --> 01:20:25.571
Did you know there's a rumor
circulating that he's dead?

1122
01:20:25.654 --> 01:20:26.822
You hear me?

1123
01:20:26.905 --> 01:20:29.199
The media is having a feeding frenzy
over this.

1124
01:20:29.283 --> 01:20:31.035
All the phone lines are jammed,

1125
01:20:31.118 --> 01:20:32.703
and every network has a pirated shot

1126
01:20:32.786 --> 01:20:35.039
of Marlon making an ass of himself
in front of the camera.

1127
01:20:35.122 --> 01:20:37.333
The sponsors are threatening
to rip up their contracts.

1128
01:20:37.416 --> 01:20:38.834
Why? We're getting higher ratings
with this graphic

1129
01:20:38.917 --> 01:20:42.004
than we've ever had on this show.

1130
01:20:44.923 --> 01:20:46.216
<i>No sign of him.</i>

1131
01:20:46.383 --> 01:20:49.178
Marlon, why don't you head back to town
and join the others?

1132
01:20:49.261 --> 01:20:52.222
Everyone else is at first positions, okay?
Thank you.

1133
01:20:53.766 --> 01:20:55.976
Everyone's at first positions, right?

1134
01:21:01.607 --> 01:21:03.484
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

1135
01:21:11.367 --> 01:21:14.870
SIMEON: We've got the light.
So he's got to be there somewhere.

1136
01:21:17.664 --> 01:21:19.375
We're not watching the sea.

1137
01:21:19.458 --> 01:21:22.002
SIMEON: Hang on a minute.
Why would we watch the sea?

1138
01:21:22.628 --> 01:21:23.962
Sweep the harbor.

1139
01:21:24.129 --> 01:21:25.672
SIMEON: Bring up the harbor cameras.

1140
01:21:25.756 --> 01:21:28.092
OPERATOR: Shift all harbor cameras
to computer, please.

1141
01:21:28.175 --> 01:21:29.802
SIMEON: Some of those are out,
aren't they?

1142
01:21:29.885 --> 01:21:31.136
OPERATOR: Yeah.
We have four of them down,

1143
01:21:31.220 --> 01:21:33.305
but we have the lighthouse cameras up.

1144
01:21:33.389 --> 01:21:35.849
-OPERATOR: All buoy cams, please.
-MOSES: What's happening?

1145
01:21:36.975 --> 01:21:38.602
OPERATOR: Long-lens,
shore-based cameras.

1146
01:21:38.685 --> 01:21:39.728
MOSES: Why are we looking
at the water?

1147
01:21:39.812 --> 01:21:40.813
OPERATOR: Good.

1148
01:21:40.896 --> 01:21:42.731
Pan and zoom please.

1149
01:21:46.110 --> 01:21:47.319
Truman,

1150
01:21:49.488 --> 01:21:50.989
where are you going?

1151
01:21:52.950 --> 01:21:54.827
How can he sail? He's in insurance.

1152
01:21:54.910 --> 01:21:57.413
-MOSES: Isn't he terrified of the water?
-Resume transmission.

1153
01:21:57.496 --> 01:21:59.081
Resuming transmission.

1154
01:22:01.208 --> 01:22:02.584
(CHUCKLING)

1155
01:22:04.294 --> 01:22:07.423
-I got 2-to-1 he doesn't make it.
-MAN: I want a piece of that.

1156
01:22:07.506 --> 01:22:09.591
2-to-1 he doesn't make it.

1157
01:22:11.969 --> 01:22:13.679
Just leave them in the car.

1158
01:22:26.733 --> 01:22:30.612
Let's get off this mast shot. We can't
see his face. Go to the cabin cam.

1159
01:22:33.615 --> 01:22:35.159
There. Perfect.

1160
01:22:36.118 --> 01:22:37.661
That's our hero shot.

1161
01:23:03.270 --> 01:23:05.063
Let's get another boat out there.

1162
01:23:05.147 --> 01:23:08.400
Okay. Listen, Gus, I need you to talk
to the guys on the ferry.

1163
01:23:08.484 --> 01:23:10.986
Come on. Get it moving.
Get it out of here.

1164
01:23:11.069 --> 01:23:12.738
(ENGINE FALTERING)

1165
01:23:13.280 --> 01:23:14.531
GUS: Come on.

1166
01:23:15.115 --> 01:23:18.744
-I'm usually the bus driver.
-Bottom line is they can't drive the boat.

1167
01:23:18.952 --> 01:23:20.245
They're actors.

1168
01:23:24.708 --> 01:23:26.168
How do we stop him?

1169
01:23:36.595 --> 01:23:37.804
Okay.

1170
01:23:40.307 --> 01:23:43.936
We're going to be accessing
the weather program now.

1171
01:23:44.603 --> 01:23:47.606
So hold onto your hats. You got that?

1172
01:23:48.774 --> 01:23:52.945
No. I think we're gonna want to localize
the storm over the boat.

1173
01:23:56.031 --> 01:23:58.033
You can get the coordinates for that.

1174
01:23:58.116 --> 01:24:00.744
There's no rescue boat.
He won't know what to do.

1175
01:24:00.827 --> 01:24:03.121
He'll turn back. He'll be too afraid.

1176
01:24:06.542 --> 01:24:07.918
Thar she blows.

1177
01:24:18.637 --> 01:24:19.680
(ENGINE FALTERING)

1178
01:24:19.763 --> 01:24:20.931
Come on.

1179
01:24:26.895 --> 01:24:28.105
(GRUNTING)

1180
01:24:44.204 --> 01:24:45.664
Give me some lightning.

1181
01:24:47.332 --> 01:24:48.417
Again.

1182
01:24:49.001 --> 01:24:50.210
Hit him again!

1183
01:25:01.930 --> 01:25:04.182
For God's sake,
the whole world is watching.

1184
01:25:04.266 --> 01:25:06.435
We can't let him die
in front of a live audience.

1185
01:25:06.518 --> 01:25:08.353
He was born in front of a live audience.

1186
01:25:36.798 --> 01:25:37.799
(ALL CHEERING)

1187
01:25:37.883 --> 01:25:39.217
Come on, Truman!

1188
01:25:42.387 --> 01:25:44.723
You can do it! Hold on!

1189
01:25:47.392 --> 01:25:48.477
(GRUNTING)

1190
01:26:03.492 --> 01:26:05.160
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1191
01:26:09.998 --> 01:26:12.084
Is that the best you can do?

1192
01:26:13.627 --> 01:26:16.755
You're gonna have to kill me!

1193
01:26:17.923 --> 01:26:20.175
<i>TRUMAN: (SINGING)
What shall we do with a drunken sailor?</i>

1194
01:26:20.258 --> 01:26:22.844
-I demand that you cease transmission.
-Keep running.

1195
01:26:22.969 --> 01:26:27.265
<i>What shall we do with a drunken sailor
Early in the mornin’?</i>

1196
01:26:27.474 --> 01:26:30.018
Increase the wind.

1197
01:26:32.437 --> 01:26:34.898
-I'm telling you for the last time.
-How close is he?

1198
01:26:34.981 --> 01:26:36.400
-Very close.
-Capsize him. Tip him over.

1199
01:26:36.483 --> 01:26:39.361
-Damn you, Christof!
-You can't. He's tied himself to the boat!

1200
01:26:39.444 --> 01:26:40.445
Shut up!

1201
01:26:40.529 --> 01:26:42.322
He's gonna drown,
and he doesn't even care.

1202
01:26:42.406 --> 01:26:43.532
-Do it.
-No.

1203
01:26:43.615 --> 01:26:44.616
Do it!

1204
01:26:47.703 --> 01:26:48.954
(WIND HOWLING)

1205
01:26:57.838 --> 01:26:59.464
(BOAT CREAKING)

1206
01:27:23.321 --> 01:27:24.573
(THUNDER CLAPPING)

1207
01:27:29.494 --> 01:27:31.163
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1208
01:27:39.296 --> 01:27:40.547
That's enough.

1209
01:27:45.552 --> 01:27:47.053
(BOAT CREAKING)

1210
01:28:10.494 --> 01:28:11.661
(RETCHING)

1211
01:29:30.407 --> 01:29:31.783
(CRASHING)

1212
01:29:59.519 --> 01:30:00.854
(EXCLAIMS)

1213
01:30:02.689 --> 01:30:03.899
(SIGHS)

1214
01:31:51.589 --> 01:31:53.133
CHRISTOF: I want to talk to him.

1215
01:32:02.058 --> 01:32:03.184
(SIGHING)

1216
01:32:12.110 --> 01:32:13.319
Truman.

1217
01:32:15.113 --> 01:32:16.406
You can speak.

1218
01:32:18.491 --> 01:32:19.784
<i>I can hear you.</i>

1219
01:32:24.330 --> 01:32:25.457
Who are you?

1220
01:32:25.582 --> 01:32:28.126
I am the creator of a television show

1221
01:32:28.209 --> 01:32:31.212
that gives hope and joy and inspiration
to millions.

1222
01:32:36.134 --> 01:32:37.385
<i>Then who am I?</i>

1223
01:32:37.802 --> 01:32:39.179
You're the star.

1224
01:32:45.268 --> 01:32:46.644
<i>Was nothing real?</i>

1225
01:32:47.270 --> 01:32:48.521
You were real.

1226
01:32:49.981 --> 01:32:52.275
That's what made you so good to watch.

1227
01:32:52.984 --> 01:32:54.527
Listen to me, Truman.

1228
01:32:54.652 --> 01:32:56.821
There's no more truth out there

1229
01:32:57.906 --> 01:33:00.533
than there is in the world
I created for you.

1230
01:33:02.494 --> 01:33:04.037
<i>The same lies,</i>

1231
01:33:05.747 --> 01:33:07.082
<i>the same deceit.</i>

1232
01:33:08.041 --> 01:33:09.459
But in my world

1233
01:33:11.294 --> 01:33:13.004
you have nothing to fear.

1234
01:33:16.382 --> 01:33:18.927
<i>I know you better than
you know yourself.</i>

1235
01:33:19.010 --> 01:33:21.137
You never had a camera in my head.

1236
01:33:22.931 --> 01:33:24.182
You're afraid.

1237
01:33:25.475 --> 01:33:27.268
That's why you can't leave.

1238
01:33:31.940 --> 01:33:33.358
It's okay, Truman.

1239
01:33:34.484 --> 01:33:35.735
I understand.

1240
01:33:37.529 --> 01:33:40.031
I have been watching you
your whole life.

1241
01:33:42.826 --> 01:33:44.953
I was watching when you were born.

1242
01:33:47.372 --> 01:33:49.916
I was watching
when you took your first step.

1243
01:33:54.212 --> 01:33:56.714
<i>I watched you on your first day
of school.</i>

1244
01:33:58.091 --> 01:33:59.509
<i>(CHRISTOF CHUCKLES)</i>

1245
01:33:59.592 --> 01:34:02.137
The episode when you lost
your first tooth.

1246
01:34:06.599 --> 01:34:08.309
You can't leave, Truman.

1247
01:34:09.936 --> 01:34:11.354
Please, God.

1248
01:34:11.437 --> 01:34:12.897
<i>You belong here…</i>

1249
01:34:13.106 --> 01:34:14.315
You can do it.

1250
01:34:16.234 --> 01:34:17.443
...with me.

1251
01:34:19.946 --> 01:34:21.239
Talk to me.

1252
01:34:22.615 --> 01:34:23.867
Say something.

1253
01:34:28.288 --> 01:34:31.416
Say something, God damn it.
You're on television.

1254
01:34:31.791 --> 01:34:33.793
<i>You’re live to the whole world.</i>

1255
01:34:51.436 --> 01:34:53.271
In case I don't see you,

1256
01:34:54.439 --> 01:34:56.983
good afternoon, good evening,
and good night.

1257
01:35:00.195 --> 01:35:01.237
Yeah.

1258
01:35:24.344 --> 01:35:25.762
ALL: Yeah!

1259
01:35:35.480 --> 01:35:38.524
-He made it! Yeah!
-All right, Truman!

1260
01:35:48.368 --> 01:35:50.870
-Cease transmission.
-Ceasing transmission.

1261
01:35:55.583 --> 01:35:57.877
-You want another slice?
-No. I'm okay.

1262
01:35:58.378 --> 01:36:00.338
What else is on?
Where's the <i>TV Guide?</i>

